resource.http://dev.llgc.org.uk/sas/full_text: 'in his dayes': this phrase indicates that, although the Polyhymnia manuscript was copied after 1648, this poem was written prior to Norris's death in 1622. Norris was only made Earl of Berkshire  on 28 January 1621, so the poem may have been written between this date and his death the following year, or Basse may be applying the title retrospectively.

resource.http://dev.llgc.org.uk/sas/full_text:
Some men in honour of Heroicall freinds

With arms & tropheys carue their fronted walls,

Others in memory, and like gratefull ends,

With pictures, people their delightfull halls.

Another sort, for favours shew’d, expends

Some time & meanes in frolique festivalls.

   All from the blamelesse threshold to exclude

   The monstrous foote of base ingratitude.
